The number of new recruits from Ukraine preparing to be sent to Donbass has been named
The official representative of the People’s Militia of the self-proclaimed Luhansk People’s Republic (LPR), Andrei Marochko, said that in the winter of 2018-2019, Ukraine will send at least 3,000 recruits to Donbas.
According to him, in this way Kiev plans to “at least somehow complement the units.”
"The unwillingness of Ukrainian citizens to serve in the ranks of the Armed Forces of Ukraine, mass dismissals have led to low staffing of units," Marochko said, quoted by RIA Novosti.
He also did not rule out that the real numbers of Ukrainians drafted into the army can be increased if necessary.
In 2014-2017, Kiev launched the so-called anti-terrorist operation (ATO), which was later replaced by the Joint Forces Operation (JFO).
It was assumed that this measure would strengthen the role of Ukrainian security forces in the settlement of the situation.
At the end of August 2018, the situation in the Donbass worsened due to the murder of the head of the DPR Alexander Zakharchenko.
The DPR authorities have classified the incident as a terrorist attack.
During the investigation of the criminal case, several people involved in the explosion were detained.
According to preliminary data, they confirmed that the sabotage was organized by the Ukrainian special services.
U.S. forces Musk to resign as chairman of Tesla’s board
American businessman Elon Musk will leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of the company he founded Tesla at the request of the US authorities.
To resolve the claims of the Federal Securities and Exchange Commission, the entrepreneur will also pay $20 million.
According to CNBC, the pre-trial agreement with the agency allows Musk to remain in a leadership position at Tesla.
At the same time, he is obliged to pay $20 million and leave the post of chairman of the board of directors within 45 days from the date of the agreement and for at least three years.
Two independent directors will be appointed in its place.
It is specified that the agreement still has to be approved by the court.
On September 28, it became known that the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission accused Musk of misleading shareholders with a statement about the availability of sufficient funds to buy back the shares of this company and filed a lawsuit against the entrepreneur.
It is about the publication of the businessman on Twitter, where he said that he wanted to buy back Tesla shares for $420 per share, but did not do it.
After the tweet, the company's shares grew by almost 11%.
The head of the British foreign Ministry compared the EU with the Soviet Union and prison
British Foreign Secretary Jeremy Hunt compared the European Union to the Soviet Union and accused Brussels of capturing members of the community.
This statement was made by the diplomat at the Congress of the ruling Conservative Party in Birmingham, which opened on Sunday, September 30.
As the Daily Mail notes, in this way Hunt commented on the difficulties in the Brexit negotiation process.
What happened to the belief in the European dream and its ideals?
The EU was created to protect freedom, and the Soviet Union did not allow anyone to leave it.
The lesson of history is clear: if you turn the EU from a community into a prison, the desire to leave it will not diminish, but will only grow, and we will not be the only prisoner who wants to escape from captivity.
He also added that attempts to punish Britain for the decision to leave the European Union will only aggravate the crisis.
In mid-September, British Prime Minister Theresa May said Brexit talks were at a standstill.
This is how she commented on the results of the informal EU summit in Salzburg.
The decision on Brexit was made in 2016 following the results of the referendum.
The UK is expected to leave before April 2019, but negotiations with Brussels on this issue are complicated by a number of factors.
In particular, there is still no clear agreement on how the parties will interact after London leaves the community.
The issue of the Irish border remains open.
