Elon Musk forced to leave the post of chairman of the board of directors of Tesla
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over fraud.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, within the framework of the agreements reached, Musk will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of Tesla's head.
The founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $20 million.
A similar amount will be demanded from Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur, included in the list of 50 richest people planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of SpaceX, the neurotechnology company Neuralink and the developer of electric cars Tesla, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission earlier sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The share price of $420 was set allegedly “due to the importance of this number in the marijuana culture”, Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the co-director of the security department of the commission Stephen Peikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considered the allegations of fraud to be unfounded, and added that he was very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Integrity is the most important value in my life and the facts will prove that I did not violate it in any way,” the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a collective lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the businessman's posts had caused them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the tweets of the businessman were misleading, as a result of which the sellers of shares of Tesla were forced to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Also, other plaintiffs noted that the careless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk was also accused of stock market fraud by the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would face suspension from the company’s management and even prison.
This, in particular, said CNBC former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is “a good guy who can’t run a car company.”
