In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 prisoners have escaped from a prison in the Indonesian province of Central Sulawesi.
The escape was made possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when detainees in the prison in the city of Palu demanded their release in connection with the tremors.
More than 340 prisoners rioted and set fire to the facility.
Arriving at the scene of the emergency, the police partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself was seriously damaged, and guards were struggling to hold the prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi has increased to 832 people.
As a result, it is still not possible to establish transport, electricity and connections to certain areas of the island.
"Golden Pearl" for "Ultimate Realism"
The San Sebastian International Film Festival for the third time in history recognized the best film of the year Spanish film.
The main award - "Golden Shell" - was awarded to the drama "Between two seas" directed by Isaac Lacuesta.
This film with almost documentary realism tells the difficult story of the life of two brothers in the Spanish seaside province of Cádiz - Lacuesta presented a continuation of his 2006 film "The Legend of Time".
At the awards ceremony of the film festival in San Sebastian, the creators of the Argentine thriller "Red", which was awarded in several nominations, were honored.
Benjamin Naishtat was named Director of the Year, Pedro Sotero was awarded for his camera work, and Dario Grandinetti was recognized as the best actor.
Actress of the year at the San Sebastian Film Festival was Pia Tielta from Norway.
The jury praised her participation in the film "Blind Spot" - a drama about the life of a family after the attempted suicide of her daughter.
The film became the directorial debut of Swedish actress Tuva Novotna.
In the nomination for "Best Screenplay", the winner was shared by the films "July" and "Faithful Man".
The jury won a special prize for the Philippine crime drama “Alpha: The Right to Murder”.
Dizziness, tears and laughter
The festival in San Sebastian is considered one of the main cultural events in Spain and one of the most important European film competitions.
About his impressions from the festival Euronews said the owner of the "Golden Shell" director Isaki Lacuesta:
That was wonderful!
We came here as a whole team and of course we experienced dizzying moments, tears, laughter.
We're happy.
We started making this film 14 years ago, it was a very long job, and what’s especially important to me is that we didn’t want to stop.
Now is the time of joy and gratitude.
As noted by Euronews correspondent Carlos Marlasca, the film of Isaac Lacuesta organically fit into the collection of paintings that received "Golden shells", "but the festival in San Sebastian did not do without unexpected, sometimes shocking decisions of the jury, which sometimes even called the calling card of the competition".
