The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the isolation of penicillin from mold mushrooms was not Fleming’s first discovery.
A few years earlier, when he had a cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (a kind of glass lid in which experiments with bacteria are carried out) and a few days later he discovered that the bacteria that were there had been destroyed.
They also found penicillin by accident.
Fleming’s name was included in the list of the 100 most outstanding personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases, previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene ...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, Parisian newspapers wrote: "To defeat fascism and liberate France, he did more than dozens of divisions."
According to experts, Fleming’s discovery of the world’s first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million inhabitants of the Earth.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in the famous St Paul’s Cathedral in London.
Where, by the way, my wife and I turned our attention to this talkative Russian-speaking guide.
And a few years later, the statue of Alexander Fleming in full growth, we had the opportunity to observe in the most unexpected place for this in the capital of Spain.
There, near the main arena for holding the bullfight Plaza de Toros de Las Ventas, the famous Spanish matadors erected a monument to the man by whose efforts, in their opinion, the lives of hundreds of outstanding masters of the bullfight were saved.
