Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it can become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
“The uniqueness of this 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric to which we have almost become accustomed in recent years with regard to Russia has now been an order of magnitude more subdued,” the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by Rossiyskaya Gazeta.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes "marked as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which spoke quite unanimously on this issue."
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, "the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent."
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, at least, the choir was not absolutely accurate," the politician drew attention, noting that Russia "was no longer a kind of wall against which tennis ball hits are trained."
The head of the relevant committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion, “will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, two, three.”
"I do not exclude that the current session in some sense can be a turning point," Kosachev admitted, explaining that "there are too many examples of how Russia's connection manages to move forward in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an "adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving global problems of our time".
“I don’t want to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that we are somewhere passing a point beyond which the movement will no longer be a movement backwards, it will be a movement forwards,” he added.
Another “interesting and important feeling” in this context Kosachev called “the request for the Russian vision of how the modern world should develop”.
“I attended very many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of foreign Affairs Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested in the committee, but now the situation is different,” he said.
“The so-called new liberal order, which is embodied in the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve the world’s problems due to the obvious shortage of ideas in the global space, the shortage of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problems of migration.”
"And here the request for a Russian vision becomes more and more obvious," Kosachev said, stressing that in this sense he considers "the current session successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
