AfD became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” is breaking another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
Apparently, Germans have grown tired of Angela Merkel’s immigration policy, which has made the country a desirable destination for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most clearly shown by the latest polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party “Alternative for Germany” is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, climbing to the second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
The right-wing Conservatives, with 17 percent popularity, managed to beat the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is worth noting the fact that the AfD, created in 2013, from a small group of Eurosceptic economists, managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings so far continues to hold the ruling bloc CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also falling.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
The Social Democrats were followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The Evolution of "Alternatives"
The Alternative for Germany party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s policy, but initially dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany’s “sponsorship” of the weak EU economies, did not exclude the possibility of a return to the German mark and a full exit of the country from the European Union.
Against the backdrop of the deepening immigration crisis, the political platform of the AfD has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party that took over the Eurosceptic niche and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, winning 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the Alternative for Germany will get seats in the European Parliament.
